Week 7

Skills

This week we will target the following skills:

  1. Understanding of simple R commands
  2. Basic navigation of RStudio interface
  3. Using functions in R
  4. Writing functions in R
  5. Using scripts in R/RStudio
  6. Install and load packages
  7. Use the help() function in R to find information
  8. Combine the skills learnt so far

Applied skills, exercises, resources.

All the references for this week link to Hands-On Programming with R, by Garrett Grolemund. You can get a physical copy of the book if you wish, but the standard and better way to access it is the free-to-use website: https://RStudio-education.github.io/hopr/index.html. The required readings for this weeks are:

  • Section 2.1

The following is a mixture of exercises and exploratory activities that you have to go through. The right approach is to first read the sources (e.g., section 2.1, 2.2), and then to go through each block in this document. Please do not advance unless you are confident you are mastering the content.

Discosure: an important part of the R world is Tidyverse. You could have seen it in a previous unit, and surely will do in future units. In this unit, we will explicitly avoid Tidyverse, as our focus is on basic/core R. Should we use anything from the Tidyverse world, as for example functions in the package ggplot2, we will do it as an example only.

1. Understanding of simple R commands [Section 2.1, 2.2]

Learning outcomes:

  • Execute operations
  • Create an object
  • Change value of objects
  • Create a numeric vector
  • Create a matrix
  • Element-wise execution
  • Inner multiplication, outer multiplication
  • Naming rules in R

Instructions:

  • Creating objects and assigning values in R: objects are assigned values using <- , an arrow formed out of < and -. An equal sign, =, can also be used. For example, the following command assigns the value 1 to the object x.
x <- 1

2. Basic navigation of RStudio interface [Section 2.1, 2.2]

Learning outcomes:

  • Learn where to write commands, and where to find objects

Instructions:

  • Explore panes in RStudio.
    • In which pane can you write commands?
    • In which pane can you explore objects?
    • What other panes can you find in RStudio? Can you guess what they are used for?
  • Change the panes layout.
    • In Tools/Global Options/Pane Layout, you can decide the layout of panes in RStudio. Experiment with it. Going on in this unit, you could decide that there is a layout that works better for you than the default one.

3. Using functions in R [Section 2.3]

Learning outcomes:

  • Understand the anatomy of a function, ie the name and the argument/s
  • Use the important functions round() and mean()
  • Can we apply a function to the result of a function?

Instructions:

  • Type and reflect on the results of the following commands:
round(3.14159)
## [1] 3
round(3.14159, 2) 
## [1] 3.14
round(x=3.14159, digits=2) 
## [1] 3.14
x <- 1:10 
mean(x) 
## [1] 5.5
round(mean(x)) 
## [1] 6
round(mean(x), digits=0) 
## [1] 6
round(mean(x), digits=2) 
## [1] 5.5
  • In the last two commands above, are the digits=0 and digits=2 arguments being used by the function round() or mean()?

6. Install and load packages [Section 3.1]

Learning outcomes:

  • Find out when and why a function is not available in R
  • If appropriate, install a package
  • If appropriate, load a package

Not all commands/functions are readily available in R. Sometimes functions are part of so-called packages. We need to load them in the environment before being able to use them. If the package is not available, we need to install it.

7. Find information on R, and its commands, using the help() function [Section 3.2]

Learning outcomes:

  • Investigate how to generate random numbers sampled from normal and uniform distributions
  • Investigate how to compute the mean and standard deviation of a numeric vector
  • Investigate how to create a scatter plot using the plot function.
  • What are the differences among the functions qplot(), plot() and histogram()?
  • The goal of the latter question is to train you to read and understand help pages. The actual differences among qplot(), plot() and histogram() are not important right now.

Instructions:

  • Generate 100 numbers sampled from the standard normal distribution using the command rnorm(100).
  • Use the help() function to find how to generate 10 numbers sampled from a normal distribution with mean mu=1 and standard deviation st.dev=2.5
  • Use the help() function to investigate the syntax of the commands mean() and sd(). Try running some code to verify your understanding.
  • Investigate the commands plot() and histogram(). Use them to check out the numbers you generated in the previous steps.
  • Often, when problems are more complex, it is easier to google your questions. As an example, can you find the command to create comparative boxplots?

Exercise 2

Write and test a function that takes in input three arguments:

  • x: a numeric vector
  • k: an integer
  • cols = c(c1, c2): a vector of two strings. c1 and c2 are colours. The default is c1=red, c2=blue

The function plots two lines (not points) in the same plot, y1=xky1=xk and y2=xk+1y2=xk+1. The colours of the two lines are set by the object cols. To solve this exercise, you need to carefully read the help page of the command plot(). Additional challenges:

  • How do you set the default value of the object cols? You can use google to find it out.
  • Can you take care of the title (main) on the graph? Hard code it in the plot command.
  • Can you use different colours for the two lines?
  • Can you insert a legend that explains which line is y1=xky1=xk and which one is y2=xk+1y2=xk+1? To solve this, you need to read the help page of the command legend().
  • Can you set the limits of the plots on the y-axis so that both functions are fully visualised?
  • when testing the function, can you choose the values of the vector x such that the plot will look good?
my_func2 <- function(x, k, cols=c('red', 'blue')){ 
  f1=x^k
  f2=x^(k+1)
  ylim=range(c(f1,f2))
    plot(x, x^k, t='l', main="Power functions", col=cols[1], ylim=ylim, ylab='')
  lines(x, x^(k+1), col=cols[2])
  legend('bottomright',legend = c(paste("x^",k,sep=''), paste("x^",k+1,sep='')), col=cols, lty=1)
} 
my_func2((-100:100)/50, 2) 

my_func2((-100:100)/50, 3, cols = c('red', 'green'))

Exercise 3

In the last exercise for this week, you are going to write a generator of random numbers according to the following model:

yi=+1x1i+2x2i+iyi=+1x1i+2x2i+i
with iN(0,2)iN(0,2).

We can rewrite the model in matrix form as:

Y=X+Y=X+
where XX is a matrix of 3 columns (vector of ones, x1x1, x2x2).

Write and test a function that takes in input the following arguments:

  • N: integer, the number of observation to generate
  • rx1: a numeric vector of length = 2, the range of x1x1
  • rx2: a numeric vector of length = 2, the range of x2x2
  • beta: a vector (,1,2)(,1,2)
  • sigma: the standard deviation

and:

  • generates the values of YY
  • plots x1x1 vs YY and x2x2 vs YY in two distinct plots, using points. If you have time, you could look at the command par(mfrow=c(1,2)) to display both plots in the same graph (or, in R lingo, in the same device).

In the function, an elegant solution is to use a matrix XX to generate YY. To do this, you should first generate the values of x1x1 and x2x2 in the given ranges rx1 and rx2 (e.g., using the function seq(), the function runif(), or both), and then create XX, a matrix with N rows and 3 columns. The first column is a vector of N ones and accounts for the intercept (use the function rep()), while the second and third columns are x1x1 and x2x2.

my_gen_func <- function(N, rx1, rx2, beta, sigma){
  X = cbind(rep(1, N), seq(rx1[1], rx1[2], len=N), runif(N, min=rx2[1], max=rx2[2]))
  Y = t(beta %*% t(X)) + rnorm(N, 0, sigma)
  par(mfrow=c(1,2))
  plot(X[,2], Y, xlab="x1")
  plot(X[,3], Y, xlab="x2", col='red')
  par(mfrow=c(1,1))
} 
my_gen_func(100, c(0,10), c(2,12), beta=c(1,5,7), sigma=1)
